UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=30, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Every Texas title traces back to one of four sovereigns: Spain, Mexico, the Republic of Texas, or the State of Texas.','Texas retained its public domain at annexation, so its land was never federal public domain and has no township-range PLSS grid.','The sovereign grant (Spanish/Mexican ''title'' or Republic/State ''patent'') is the instrument that severs land from the sovereign.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Identify the four sovereigns of the soil in Texas and the order in which they granted land.','Explain why Texas has no federal Public Land Survey System (PLSS) across most of the state.','Distinguish a sovereign ''title'' or ''patent'' from later private deeds in the chain of title.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='6dc25256-cb35-42e0-b8ec-90b29f6c7085';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='6dc25256-cb35-42e0-b8ec-90b29f6c7085';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=32, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Mexican Texas was settled through empresario contracts that granted land in exchange for bringing in families, subject to religion, allegiance, and residency conditions.','Spanish and Mexican grants are sized in varas, labors, and leagues—not feet and acres directly.','Many South/Central Texas titles still trace to a Mexican-era league-and-labor grant held in the GLO Spanish Collection.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Describe the empresario/colonization system used in Mexican Texas and its conditions on settlers.','Convert among the vara, labor, and league units used in Spanish and Mexican grants.','Explain why many South and Central Texas chains of title bottom out in a Mexican-era grant.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='5ea5e4f0-f3c6-48af-a855-054e9110356e';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='5ea5e4f0-f3c6-48af-a855-054e9110356e';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=28, key_takeaways=ARRAY['The Republic of Texas distributed huge acreage through headright certificates redeemed for patents.','On annexation in 1845, Texas retained all of its vacant and unappropriated public lands—the federal government did not take the public domain.','Texas dedicated public-land revenue to the Permanent School Fund.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Explain the headright certificate system used by the Republic of Texas.','Describe how Texas retained its public lands at annexation in 1845.','Relate Republic-era land distribution to the Permanent School Fund.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='184ab3e2-3b90-48ae-b9a1-be10d4e85a55';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='184ab3e2-3b90-48ae-b9a1-be10d4e85a55';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=30, key_takeaways=ARRAY['The GLO, founded in 1836, is the oldest existing Texas state agency and the custodian of the State''s original land-grant records.','The GLO archive (the Spanish Collection, field notes, sketches, maps) is the starting point for retracing original Texas surveys.','The GLO still issues patents and administers state lands; state-land surveys require a Licensed State Land Surveyor (LSLS).']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Describe the role and history of the Texas General Land Office.','Explain how the GLO archive supports retracement of original land-grant surveys.','Identify the GLO''s continuing function of issuing patents and the LSLS credential for state-land work.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='e5580ef9-dc1d-436a-80df-6e83e08e5a71';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='e5580ef9-dc1d-436a-80df-6e83e08e5a71';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=30, key_takeaways=ARRAY['The chain of title is the sequence of conveyances from the sovereign to the present owner; the abstract is the documented summary of that history.','Title insurance indemnifies against covered title defects; it does not certify a clean chain the way an attorney''s opinion or abstract examination does.','Surveyors interact with the abstract through the original survey/abstract number and through survey exceptions on a title commitment.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Define the abstract of title and the chain of title.','Explain the role of title insurance in Texas and how it differs from an abstract.','Distinguish marketable title from a defective or clouded title.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='f0ebedbb-846c-4687-bac9-e799499718b8';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='f0ebedbb-846c-4687-bac9-e799499718b8';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=32, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Texas records instruments in the county where the land lies; recording gives constructive notice to all persons.','Texas is a pure ''notice'' state: a later purchaser for value without notice prevails over a prior unrecorded grantee even without winning the race to record.','Constructive notice arises from the records (§13.002) and from visible, open, exclusive, and unequivocal possession.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Explain where and how real-property instruments are recorded in Texas (Property Code Ch. 11–13).','Apply the Texas notice-recording rule and identify a bona fide purchaser.','Use the county deed records and GLO records to research a chain of title.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='a1904e23-948b-4673-8fc9-cf711ada59a0';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='a1904e23-948b-4673-8fc9-cf711ada59a0';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=30, key_takeaways=ARRAY['General warranty, special warranty, and quitclaim deeds differ in the scope of title protection they convey.','Texas construes a deed by the parties'' intent within the four corners; the dignity-of-calls hierarchy is a subordinate aid.','A quitclaim conveys only the grantor''s interest ''if any'' and is not a muniment of title; its grantee is generally not a BFP, subject to the 2021 four-year window.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Distinguish the principal Texas deed types and the warranties each carries.','State the controlling rule of construction (intent within the four corners) and the dignity-of-calls hierarchy.','Explain why a Texas quitclaim grantee is generally not a bona fide purchaser, and how §13.006 (2021) softened the rule.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='768c4969-7fca-4dfe-a552-3a375e926869';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='768c4969-7fca-4dfe-a552-3a375e926869';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Vara-to-feet conversions and labor/league acreage calculations are routine when retracing original Texas grants.','1 vara = 33⅓ in = 2.7778 ft; 36 varas = 100 ft exactly; 1 acre = 43,560 sq ft.','A practical title search combines GLO sovereign records with county deed records and the Texas notice rule.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Convert vara-based grant dimensions to feet and back using the statutory vara.','Compute the acreage of a labor or league from square varas.','Apply chain-of-title and recording rules to a realistic Texas research scenario.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='d12cd2e7-2324-47e0-b1f5-ae908b7963e2';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='d12cd2e7-2324-47e0-b1f5-ae908b7963e2';
  'eeee1550-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Vara-to-feet conversion of a grant dimension', 'Vara-to-feet conversion of a grant dimension', 'Texas Land Titles — Historical Units', 'Vara conversion', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'An original Texas field note for a grant boundary calls a distance of {{vrs}} varas. Using the statutory Texas vara (33⅓ in = 2.7778 ft), what is this distance in feet?', 'vrs * 2.7778', '{"decimals":1,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.5}', '[{"name":"vrs","type":"integer","min":150,"max":2500}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Identify the conversion factor","calculation_template":"1 vara = 33⅓ in = 2.7778 ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Multiply varas by the factor","result_template":"{{vrs}} × 2.7778 = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'The statutory Texas vara is 33⅓ in = 2.7778 ft, so {{vrs}} varas × 2.7778 = {{_answer}} ft. (Equivalently {{vrs}} ÷ 0.36.)', 'c100000f-0000-0000-0000-00000000000f', ARRAY['buildout','module-15','practice']::text[], true, 'buildout:m15');
  'eeee1550-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Acreage of a square Spanish/Mexican grant from a vara dimension', 'Acreage of a square Spanish/Mexican grant from a vara dimension', 'Texas Land Titles — Historical Units', 'Grant acreage', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A square portion of an original Spanish/Mexican grant measures {{side}} varas on each side. Using the statutory vara (2.7778 ft/vara) and 43,560 sq ft per acre, what is the area of this square tract in acres?', 'pow(side * 2.7778, 2) / 43560', '{"decimals":1,"unit":"acres","tolerance":1}', '[{"name":"side","type":"integer","min":500,"max":5000}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"sideFt","formula":"side * 2.7778"},{"name":"areaSqFt","formula":"pow(side * 2.7778, 2)"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Convert the side to feet","calculation_template":"{{side}} × 2.7778 = {{sideFt:f1}} ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Square the side for area in sq ft","calculation_template":"{{sideFt:f1}}² = {{areaSqFt:f0}} sq ft"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Convert to acres","result_template":"{{areaSqFt:f0}} ÷ 43,560 = {{_answer}} acres"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'A square {{side}} varas on a side is {{sideFt:f1}} ft on a side; its area is {{areaSqFt:f0}} sq ft, which is {{_answer}} acres. (A 1,000-vara square is a labor ≈ 177 ac; a 5,000-vara square is a league ≈ 4,428 ac.)', 'c100000f-0000-0000-0000-00000000000f', ARRAY['buildout','module-15','practice']::text[], true, 'buildout:m15');
COMMIT;
